Consumer Information Interface (CII) via Consumer Information Port (CIP)
**Introduction to the CII via CIP Project Study** -------------------------------------------------- This study examines the legal obligation, established by the Swiss Electricity Supply Act (LApEl), its ordinances, and regulations, to make measurement data from smart meters accessible online via the Consumer Information Interface (CII) through the Consumer Information Port (CIP). It evaluates how this obligation can be fulfilled through scenarios and approaches aligned with a corporate energy distributor’s strategy. The study identifies key regulatory constraints, applicable standards (including IDIS and the Dutch DSMR P1 standard), and analyzes their influence on strategic objectives. Scenarios are assessed based on strengths, weaknesses, opportunities, and risks, ensuring alignment with strategic goals. Value propositions emphasize the business benefits of achieving these objectives. Models are provided to establish the general business context and analyze business processes at varying levels of detail. These serve as the foundation for application usage scenarios, exploring integrations and technology solutions, with a particular focus on the BPA with RPA scenario. Additionally, a capability maturity level assessment evaluates the benefits of proposed architectural transitions. Conducted unilaterally in 2024 by Michel Wicky, Enterprise and Solutions Architect ([LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/in/michelwicky)), in collaboration with [Inoshift](https://inoshift.com/), this study was an independent initiative to showcase acquired expertise in enterprise, solution, and systems architecture within the energy sector. It follows the TOGAF ADM cycle, with documentation aligned to ISO standards 42010, 25010, and 27001 (In alignment with 62443 for the Smart Metering part). This document offers a comprehensive enterprise architecture perspective applied to an opportunity study in the energy distribution sector. Conducted independently and without external validation, it serves as a preliminary framework for reflection, improvement, or future project planning. We recommend starting with **View 0.1: Study and Project Context and Structure**, which provides an complete overview of the study's background and organization. Thank you for your interest and any feedback that may help refine this work.
